    <h1>About John Cho</h1>

    <p>Money was never far from the conversation growing up. My parents immigrated from Korea in the late seventies with very little, and every decision revolved around what things cost. But knowing money is tight and knowing how to actually manage it are two different things. The foundations of financial literacy were something I had to piece together on my own.</p>

    <p>I carried that into adulthood, and for a while, I managed fine. I was naturally frugal and practical. Then a relationship changed everything. I trusted the wrong person, took on over six figures in debt, and had to start over completely. It was the hardest period of my life. Some days I couldn't breathe.</p>

    <p>But I made a choice: do something about it, or feel sorry for myself. I pitched myself for a promotion, took on three jobs at once, and paid off every dollar in two and a half years. I'm not a financial expert. No credentials, no bestseller. What I do have is lived experience, a lot of research, and a real understanding of what it feels like to be overwhelmed by money and not know where to start.</p>

    <p>Paying off the debt was the start, not the finish. I kept going, and by 37 I had built a net worth of more than $600,000, well above average for my age, on an ordinary income and a lot of boring, consistent habits. I made plenty of mistakes along the way, and you will read about those too, because they tend to be more useful than the wins.</p>

    <p>That's why I built this site. It's for anyone who wants to take control of their finances but doesn't know how to begin, especially young adults who want to set themselves up right from the start.</p>

    <p>Everything here is general education, not personalized financial advice. Think of it as a knowledgeable friend sharing what worked, not a professional prescribing a plan.</p>
  </article>
